She signed to British record label 4AD in 2020, and released her second studio album, Sensational, in 2021.
Erika de Casier was born in 1989 or 1990 in Portugal to a Belgian mother and Cape Verdean father.
At age 16, she spent a year living with a host family in the United States.
Starting in 2014, Casier performed with Andreas Vasegaard as part of the R&B duo Saint Cava.
The duo performed at the Roskilde Festival in 2015 and released a string of singles through Danish record label Forbandet Ungdom before eventually disbanding.
In 2017, Casier released her debut single as an independent artist, "What U Wanna Do?", and released her second single, "Intimate", the following year.
In 2017, Casier released her debut single as an independent artist, "What U Wanna Do?", and released her second single, "Intimate", the following year.

She released her debut studio album, Essentials, on 16 May 2019 through her own label, Independent Jeep Records, which spawned the two prior singles as well as the singles "Good Time" and "Do My Thing".

Essentials was well received by critics, and appeared on several lists of the best albums of the year from publications including Vice, Crack Magazine, and Gorilla vs. Bear, which also named Essentials as one of the best albums of the 2010s.

Her April 2020 remix of English singer Dua Lipa's single "Physical" appeared on the remix EP for the song.
She performed a set for Boiler Room's Streaming from Isolation series in May 2020.

In October 2020, she signed to UK record label 4AD and released her first single with the label, "No Butterflies, No Nothing", which also served as the lead single from her second studio album, Sensational, with a music video.
The Fader named the single as one of the best songs of 2020.
In March 2021, she released her second single from Sensational, "Drama".
Casier announced the title of Sensational and its scheduled release date, and released her third single from the album, "Polite", in April 2021.
The fourth single from the album, "Busy", was released in May 2021.
Casier's music is mostly pop, R&B, and experimental pop, and has taken inspiration from music of the 1990s and early 2000s, incorporating genres such as g-funk, bossa nova, and breakbeat.
